{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4ec17e0d-6596-4d87-857b-47e7c22da733","content":"Since MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 defaults to VSTest when you set `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`, here's what to change:\n\n### 1. Remove (or flip) the property in your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<!-- Remove this line entirely, or set to false: -->\n<!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n```\n\nMSTest.Sdk ≥ 3.4 already defaults to **Microsoft.Testing.Platform**, so simply removing `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` enables it.\n\n### 2. Update your test runner command\n```bash\n# Old (VSTest)\ndotnet test\n\n# New (works the same, but now uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform under the hood)\ndotnet test\n```\n\n`dotnet test` still works — the SDK wires up the new platform automatically.\n\n### 3. If you use a `.runsettings` file\nMost settings carry over, but review the [migration docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/testing/microsoft-testing-platform-overview) for any platform-specific differences (e.g., custom test adapters or loggers).\n\n### 4. CI / IDE notes\n- **Visual Studio 2022 17.10+** and **VS Code** support Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively.\n- If your CI uses `dotnet test`, no command changes are needed.\n- If your CI invokes `vstest.console.exe` directly, switch to `dotnet test` or the generated test executable.\n\n**TL;DR** — just delete `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`. The SDK handles the rest.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fc282818-ec94-467a-9338-5643011a46c9","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"083A:16A6CA:7F517FE:8D86BB8:69EABE7B"},"id":"a9fd1817-e714-47f9-b6c5-4134528ddca0","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:51:18.315Z","parentId":"1a456d25-cd2c-4a32-a924-8fe877b040b5"}
